## Main Stories
1.  **Lusambo jailed for property crimes**  
    Former Lusaka Province Minister Bowman Lusambo was sentenced to three years imprisonment with hard labour by the Lusaka Magistrates’ Court for possession of property reasonably suspected to be proceeds of crime.
2.  **Government confident of 2026 victory**  
    Chief Government Spokesperson Cornelius Mweetwa stated the UPND will easily win the 2026 elections, citing President Hakainde Hichilema's performance exceeding expectations and citizens' recognition of progress.
3.  **Zambia-Sweden launch €5.2m energy project**  
    The Zambian and Swedish governments launched the Energy Efficiency for Sustainable Livelihoods in Africa (EELA) project, worth €5.2 million over four years, to promote energy efficiency interventions. It will be implemented by UNIDO in partnership with Zambian ministries and ZABS.
4.  **Malanji, Yamba sentenced to prison**  
    The Lusaka Magistrate’s Court sentenced former Foreign Affairs Minister Joseph Malanji to four years imprisonment with hard labour for possessing property suspected of being proceeds of crime, and former Secretary to the Treasury Fredson Yamba to three years for failure to follow procedure. Their sentences run concurrently.
5.  **ZRA launches Integrity Month in Mongu**  
    The Zambia Revenue Authority launched its annual Integrity Month in Mongu at Mutelo House, with Commissioner General Dingani Banda emphasizing the critical need for integrity in domestic revenue mobilization amidst reduced external aid.
6.  **ZANACO profit grows 24% to K874m**  
    Zambia National Commercial Bank (ZANACO) recorded a profit after tax of K874 million for the year ended June 30, representing 24% growth, driven by a 20% increase in operating income and growth in its loan book and digital transactions.
7.  **ZRA plans Katima-Mulilo border upgrade**  
    Zambia Revenue Authority Commissioner General Dingani Banda stated that ZRA is engaging Namibian counterparts to upgrade the Katima-Mulilo border post in Sesheke to a One-Stop-Border-Post, recognizing its importance for trade via the Walvis Bay corridor.

